 political power and deploys it on behalf of its pro-gun agenda.Taking readers from the 1930s to the age of Donald Trump, Matthew Lacombe traces how the NRA's immense influence on national politics arises from its ability to shape the political outlooks and actions of its supporters. He draws on nearly a century of archival records and surveys to show how the organization has fashioned a distinct worldview around gun ownership and used it to mobilize its supporters. Lacombe reveals how the NRA's cultivation of a large, unified, and active base has enabled it to build a resilient alliance with the Republican Party, and examines why the NRA and its members formed an important base that helped fuel the unlikely political rise of Donald Trump.Firepower sheds vital new light on how the NRA has grown powerful by mobilizing average Americans, and how it uses its GOP alliance to advance its objectives and shape the national agenda.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aFirearms ownersxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aFirearms ownershipxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aGun controlzUnited States. 0aPressure groupszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican Rifleman.  aAmerican political development.  aCharlton Heston nra.  aCharlton Heston.  aColumbine.  aGeorge Wood Wingate.  aLiberal Gun Club.  aSandy Hook.  aTea Party.  aWashington lobbyists.  aWayne LaPierre.  aWilliam Conant Church.  abump stocks.  aculture war.  aelementary school shooting.  agun control.  agun owner identity.  agun politics.  agun rights.  agun safety.  aidentity politics.  alobbying.  amass shooting statistics.  amilitias.  amixed methods.  anra influence.  anra money.  anra power.  apolarization.  apolitical parties.  asocial identity.  ate